[2]
Date: Fri 6 Mar 2015
From: Jim Alexander <james.alexander@dshs.state.tx.us> [edited]


The advice you provided regarding animals exposed to rabies ("Secondly, vaccinating and holding them in quarantine at their veterinary clinic for 3 weeks would be adequate, and, if necessary, they could have been revaccinated before being released.") is in conflict with the Rabies Compendium (http://www.nasphv.org/Documents/RabiesCompendium.pdf).

Regardless of vaccination status, exposed animals are required to be isolated for some period. I don't know if Colorado uses the Compendium's guidelines or have their own standards. In Texas we have a less restrictive standard for animals that are not current. The Compendium recommends euthanasia as the 1st option. For those owners who desire to try to salvage the exposed animal there are different requirements for vaccinated animals versus animals not current on vaccination. Currently vaccinated animals are to be vaccinated immediately and isolated for 45 days. A 6 month isolation and vaccination immediately or within 28 days of release is required for animals that are not current.

--
James L Alexander, DVM, MPVM, DACVPM
